----- Project structure (where things live) -----

This repo is organised so that each layer of the app has a clear home:
-Routes / request handling (Flask) live in app/
-HTML templates (Jinja) live in app/templates/
-Static assets (CSS/JS/images) live in app/static/
-Database connection + queries live in app/db/


This separation keeps responsibilities clean:
-Flask routes decide what to do for a given URL.
-The DB layer decides how data is stored and retrieved.
-Templates decide how pages are rendered.
-Static files add styling and interactivity.


Why this structure is used
-Lower merge conflicts: multiple people can work in different layers without stepping on each other.
-Easier debugging: if it’s a UI issue, it’s in templates/ or static/; if it’s a data issue, it’s in db/.
-Scales cleanly: new pages usually mean “add a route + template”, not copy/pasting HTML everywhere.


----- How to run locally via VSC terminal -----

Create/activate the virtual environment (Windows PowerShell):
python -m venv .venv
.\.venv\Scripts\Activate

Install dependencies:
pip install -r requirements.txt

Run Flask:
python -m app.app
Then Ctrl+click the http://127.0.0.1:5000/ link


----- Database notes (safe defaults) -----

Database credentials should not be hard-coded in Python files.
Use a .env file or environment variables (and keep .env in .gitignore).
All SQL and DB access should go through app/db/ rather than being written inside routes.


----- Rules of thumb ----- 

No SQL in route functions → put it in app/db/
No business logic in templates → keep templates focused on presentation
No API keys or any sensitive info stored in Git → use environment variables / .env (ignored)
Keep pages small → use base.html and blocks to avoid duplication